ng and state-making by exploring discourses, violence and everyday forms of survival as "idian acts that attempt to challenge or mitigate such experiences. The analysis of resistance offers a possibility to bring the historical and sociological aspects of both peacebuilding and the case of the DRC, providing new nuanced understanding on these processes and the particular case. The book also makes a significant contribution to the theorisation of resistance in International Relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relations. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh  aDemocratic Republic of Congo.  aEveryday resistance.  aHistorical Sociology.  aPeacebuilding.1 aIñiguez de Heredia, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526108784zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526108784zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526108784/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA